Therefore, divorce has not been a significant factor of population decline in The Gambia, but the marriage culture, which has gradually prevailed since the colonization has impeded migration. Women migrating into agriculture villages however, dissociate themselves from their husbands, marrying Gambian men and placing their children in an orphanage. It is estimated that about 200 Malian children growing up in the orphanages of The Gambia are in Wulari. Moffalo Siassi, the director of the NGO to which Inshaad was assigned to said that some of these children are at times bitten by dogs or riddled with starvation, a manifestation of the target of the wife migration; she further indicated that about 95% of these women are divorced from their husbands while many were malnourished at arrival and suffered from sexually transmitted diseases. Inshaad when interviewed in the Basin, said:

The first time I came here, I was unmarried so I married a Gambian and got pregnant and had my daughter child who is with me now. But now I am separated from the father, so I live with my parents, not the Gambians’ home.
